<font color="#FF0000">HMONGS IN DIFFICULTY</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 16  6:24:37 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
   The British Broadcasting Company (BBC) just released a report on the Hmongs in the United States.  They fought throughout the Vietnam War in Laos as part of America´s secret army, and after the fall of Laos to the communists, they had to flee the country for their lives.  The United States did nothing to help them for many years, forcing them to remain in squalid refugee camps in Thailand.  Only after pressure was put on the government were a number of these Vietnam War veterans allowed to come to the United States.<br>
   New laws to control welfare payments have prohibited foreign nationals from collecting social security benefits that some of the Hmong families were depending upon.  According to BBC, this has already resulted in one suicide by a Hmong woman.  The Hmongs who have settled in the United States should be eligible for American citizenship because most have been in there for about ten years.  However, the Immigration and Naturalization Service is refusing to recommend them for citizenship because it is claimed that they cannot write English well enough.  The BBC concluded that the American government is showing itself to be very ungrateful to veterans who sacrificed so much for the United States.  They might have added that this applies to American citizen veterans, as well.<br>
   I happen to personally know about the contributions of the Hmong (sometimes called Meos) in the War.  They kept the North Vietnamese supply routes in eastern Laos under pressure by attacking much superior North Vietnamese forces. The North Vietnamese therefore had to dirert many troops from their war in South Vietnam to hold off the Hmong.  If the Hmong had not been fighting, all of these troops would have been in South Vietnam trying to kill Americans.  Because of their aggessive attacks on our enemies, they took very heavy losses, and before the war ended, I had heard that they had already lost more than 10% of their entire population fighting against the communists.<br>
   Although BBC did not closely examine the reasons the Hmong residents have not been granted citizenship, I can state from personal experience that the persons working for the Immigration and Naturalization Service are no friends of Vietnam War veterans of any nationality.  The Hmongs are noted for their intelligence, and their children have generally done extremely well in American and European schools.  I cannot believe that they have language problems as the Immigration and Naturalization Service claims.  I personally believe that they are the victims of chicanery by former war protesters employed by this infamous agency.<br>
   I believe that a short e-mail inquiry to a senator or congressman would be a small favor that we could each do for a group of people who were clearly on our side when the bullets were flying and could use a little fair treatment now.<br>
   
